<body>
<p>In <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr1-1056492612455137">1997, Nutt and Backoff</xref> wrote an excellent article explaining the use and power of an organizational vision statement. Not only do I still use this article in my MBA-level strategic management class, I also use this article when I work with actual organizations to help them create a vision statement. In this article, Gioia, Nag, and Corley do a similar exemplary job of examining the relationship between a vision statement and organizational change. In similar style, Gioia and his colleagues write clearly, simply, yet very comprehensively and deeply about how having a somewhat ambiguously written vision statement might actually help organizations reach their change goals. I am sure that this article will also become a standard among those who teach about and help organizations create vision statements.</p>
